snippet.textDisplay:
In 2012, Papa John's and Schnatter received media attention after he made critical comments about the Affordable Care Act to a class on entrepreneurship.[52] In a shareholder conference call, Schnatter said that he opposed the ACA because "our best estimate is that the Obamacare will cost 11 to 14 cents per pizza".[53]
Schnatter hosted a fundraiser at his home for Republican Party candidate Mitt Romney in May 2012.[54]
Schnatter contributed to Donald Trump's 2016 presidential campaign[55] and made supportive comments about his administration in January 2017.[14]
snippet.textOriginal:
In 2012, Papa John's and Schnatter received media attention after he made critical comments about the Affordable Care Act to a class on entrepreneurship.[52] In a shareholder conference call, Schnatter said that he opposed the ACA because "our best estimate is that the Obamacare will cost 11 to 14 cents per pizza".[53]
Schnatter hosted a fundraiser at his home for Republican Party candidate Mitt Romney in May 2012.[54]
Schnatter contributed to Donald Trump's 2016 presidential campaign[55] and made supportive comments about his administration in January 2017.[14]

snippet.textDisplay:
I gotta say, I'm about thirty or so minutes in, and I just feel like Papa John is a decent dude who got a raw deal. And if corporate really did tell him not to do the show for that long, then they're batshit insane. Wow.

He's just such a friendly and charismatic dude. Any time Ethan starts talking about Papa's achievements or anything like that, Papa always deflects and it and puts the focus on the other people around him who helped him, or who he's grateful for, never just himself, and I really respect that. Even though he obviously isn't totally happy with how some things went down, and how some people behaved and treated him, he still came in and kept it super positive and I genuinely admire that in people.

Inb4 "it's just typical corporate trained CEO-ness." Maybe. So what? Regardless of why he has those skills, they're skills I respect and admire in anybody.

I'm just really glad I got to see Papa in a long-format, natural conversation instead of just out-of-context news snippets and tightly steered interviews for once.
